      import pandas as pd
      # Load both datasets
      print("Loading datasets...")
      g_dataset = pd.read_csv(r"C:\Users\HP\Documents\PM2.5 Analysis\G_Dataset_Biomarkers_PM2_5.csv")
      merged_dataset = pd.read_csv(r"C:\Users\HP\Documents\PM2.5 Analysis\merged_dataset.csv")
      print(f"g_dataset shape: {g_dataset.shape}")
      print(f"merged_dataset shape: {merged_dataset.shape}")
      # Identify columns to remove from merged_dataset
      columns_to_remove = []
      # Find columns containing 'lvef', 'lvede'
      for col in merged_dataset.columns:
          if any(keyword in col.lower() for keyword in ['lvef', 'lvede']):
              columns_to_remove.append(col)
      # Find education columns
      for col in merged_dataset.columns:
          if any(keyword in col.lower() for keyword in ['education', 'qualification', 'degree']):
              columns_to_remove.append(col)
      # Find ethnic background columns
      for col in merged_dataset.columns:
          if any(keyword in col.lower() for keyword in ['ethnic', 'ethnicity', 'background']):
              columns_to_remove.append(col)
      print(f"Columns to remove: {columns_to_remove}")
      # Remove identified columns from merged_dataset
      merged_dataset_filtered = merged_dataset.drop(columns=columns_to_remove, errors='ignore')
      print(f"Filtered merged_dataset shape: {merged_dataset_filtered.shape}")
      # Merge datasets on Participant ID
      # Assuming 'Participant ID' is the common column name
      if 'Participant ID' in g_dataset.columns and 'Participant ID' in merged_dataset_filtered.columns:
          cleaned_df = pd.merge(g_dataset, merged_dataset_filtered, on='Participant ID', how='left')
      else:
          # Try to find similar column names
          g_id_cols = [col for col in g_dataset.columns if 'participant' in col.lower() or 'id' in col.lower()]
          m_id_cols = [col for col in merged_dataset_filtered.columns if 'participant' in col.lower() or 'id' in col.lower()]
          
          print(f"Potential ID columns in g_dataset: {g_id_cols}")
          print(f"Potential ID columns in merged_dataset: {m_id_cols}")
          
          # Use the first matching column
          if g_id_cols and m_id_cols:
              cleaned_df = pd.merge(g_dataset, merged_dataset_filtered, 
                                  left_on=g_id_cols[0], right_on=m_id_cols[0], how='left')
          else:
              print("Warning: Could not find matching ID columns. Concatenating datasets.")
              cleaned_df = pd.concat([g_dataset, merged_dataset_filtered], axis=1)
      print(f"Final cleaned_df shape: {cleaned_df.shape}")
      print(f"Columns in cleaned_df: {list(cleaned_df.columns)}")
      # Display summary
      print("\nData integration completed successfully!")
      print(f"Removed {len(columns_to_remove)} columns from merged_dataset")
      print(f"Final dataset has {cleaned_df.shape[0]} rows and {cleaned_df.shape[1]} columns")

      import pandas as pd
      import numpy as np
      import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
      import seaborn as sns
      from scipy import stats
      import warnings
      warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
      # Set plotting style
      plt.style.use('default')
      sns.set_palette("husl")
      # Load the cleaned dataset (assuming it's already created from previous step)
      print("Loading cleaned dataset...")
      #cleaned_df = pd.read_csv('cleaned_df.csv') if 'cleaned_df.csv' in pd.os.listdir('.') else None
      #if cleaned_df is None:
          # If cleaned_df doesn't exist, run the data processing first
          #exec(open('data_processing_script.py').read())
      print(f"Dataset shape: {cleaned_df.shape}")
      print(f"Columns: {len(cleaned_df.columns)}")
      # ============================================================================
      # 1. BASIC DATA OVERVIEW
      # ============================================================================
      print("\n" + "="*60)
      print("1. BASIC DATA OVERVIEW")
      print("="*60)
      # Dataset info
      print(f"\nDataset Shape: {cleaned_df.shape}")
      print(f"Memory Usage: {cleaned_df.memory_usage(deep=True).sum() / 1024**2:.2f} MB")
      # Data types
      print("\nData Types:")
      data_types = cleaned_df.dtypes.value_counts()
      for dtype, count in data_types.items():
          print(f"  {dtype}: {count} columns")
      # ============================================================================
      # 2. MISSING DATA ANALYSIS
      # ============================================================================
      print("\n" + "="*60)
      print("2. MISSING DATA ANALYSIS")
      print("="*60)
      # Calculate missing values
      missing_data = pd.DataFrame({
          'Column': cleaned_df.columns,
          'Missing_Count': cleaned_df.isnull().sum(),
          'Missing_Percentage': (cleaned_df.isnull().sum() / len(cleaned_df)) * 100
      })
      missing_data = missing_data[missing_data['Missing_Count'] > 0].sort_values('Missing_Percentage', ascending=False)
      print(f"\nColumns with missing data: {len(missing_data)}")
      print(f"Total missing values: {cleaned_df.isnull().sum().sum()}")
      if len(missing_data) > 0:
          print("\nTop 20 columns with most missing data:")
          print(missing_data.head(20).to_string(index=False))
          
          # Visualize missing data pattern
          plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))
          
          # Missing data heatmap for top 30 columns with missing data
          top_missing_cols = missing_data.head(30)['Column'].tolist()
          if len(top_missing_cols) > 0:
              plt.subplot(2, 2, 1)
              sns.heatmap(cleaned_df[top_missing_cols].isnull(), cbar=True, yticklabels=False)
              plt.title('Missing Data Pattern (Top 30 Columns)')
              plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
          
          # Missing data percentage bar plot
          plt.subplot(2, 2, 2)
          top_20_missing = missing_data.head(20)
          plt.barh(range(len(top_20_missing)), top_20_missing['Missing_Percentage'])
          plt.yticks(range(len(top_20_missing)), top_20_missing['Column'])
          plt.xlabel('Missing Percentage (%)')
          plt.title('Top 20 Columns by Missing Data %')
          plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
          
          # Missing data distribution
          plt.subplot(2, 2, 3)
          missing_counts = cleaned_df.isnull().sum(axis=1)
          plt.hist(missing_counts, bins=50, alpha=0.7)
          plt.xlabel('Number of Missing Values per Row')
          plt.ylabel('Frequency')
          plt.title('Distribution of Missing Values per Row')
          
          # Missing data correlation
          plt.subplot(2, 2, 4)
          if len(top_missing_cols) > 1:
              missing_corr = cleaned_df[top_missing_cols].isnull().corr()
              sns.heatmap(missing_corr, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', center=0, 
                         square=True, fmt='.2f')
              plt.title('Missing Data Correlation')
          
          plt.tight_layout()
          plt.savefig('missing_data_analysis.png', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
          plt.show()
      # ============================================================================
      # 3. HANDLE MISSING DATA
      # ============================================================================
      print("\n" + "="*60)
      print("3. HANDLING MISSING DATA")
      print("="*60)
      # Create a copy for imputation
      cleaned_df_imputed = cleaned_df.copy()
      # Identify numerical and categorical columns
      numerical_cols = cleaned_df_imputed.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]).columns.tolist()
      categorical_cols = cleaned_df_imputed.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'category']).columns.tolist()
      print(f"\nNumerical columns: {len(numerical_cols)}")
      print(f"Categorical columns: {len(categorical_cols)}")
      # Handle numerical columns with median
      print("\nImputing numerical columns with median...")
      for col in numerical_cols:
          if cleaned_df_imputed[col].isnull().sum() > 0:
              median_val = cleaned_df_imputed[col].median()
              missing_count = cleaned_df_imputed[col].isnull().sum()
              cleaned_df_imputed[col].fillna(median_val, inplace=True)
              print(f"  {col}: {missing_count} missing values filled with median {median_val:.2f}")
      # Handle categorical columns with mode
      print("\nImputing categorical columns with mode...")
      for col in categorical_cols:
          if cleaned_df_imputed[col].isnull().sum() > 0:
              mode_val = cleaned_df_imputed[col].mode()
              if len(mode_val) > 0:
                  mode_val = mode_val[0]
                  missing_count = cleaned_df_imputed[col].isnull().sum()
                  cleaned_df_imputed[col].fillna(mode_val, inplace=True)
                  print(f"  {col}: {missing_count} missing values filled with mode '{mode_val}'")
              else:
                  print(f"  {col}: No mode found, filling with 'Unknown'")
                  cleaned_df_imputed[col].fillna('Unknown', inplace=True)
      # Verify no missing data remains
      remaining_missing = cleaned_df_imputed.isnull().sum().sum()
      print(f"\nRemaining missing values after imputation: {remaining_missing}")
      # ============================================================================
      # 4. DESCRIPTIVE STATISTICS
      # ============================================================================
      print("\n" + "="*60)
      print("4. DESCRIPTIVE STATISTICS")
      print("="*60)
      # Numerical variables summary
      print("\nNumerical Variables Summary:")
      numerical_summary = cleaned_df_imputed[numerical_cols].describe()
      print(numerical_summary.round(3))
      # Categorical variables summary
      print("\nCategorical Variables Summary:")
      for col in categorical_cols[:10]:  # Show first 10 categorical columns
          print(f"\n{col}:")
          value_counts = cleaned_df_imputed[col].value_counts()
          print(f"  Unique values: {len(value_counts)}")
          print(f"  Top 5 values:")
          for val, count in value_counts.head().items():
              print(f"    {val}: {count} ({count/len(cleaned_df_imputed)*100:.1f}%)")
      # ============================================================================
      # 5. DISTRIBUTION ANALYSIS
      # ============================================================================
      print("\n" + "="*60)
      print("5. DISTRIBUTION ANALYSIS")
      print("="*60)
      # Select key numerical columns for visualization
      key_numerical_cols = [col for col in numerical_cols if any(keyword in col.lower() 
                           for keyword in ['pm2', 'crp', 'age', 'bmi', 'cholesterol', 'glucose', 'pressure'])]
      if len(key_numerical_cols) == 0:
          key_numerical_cols = numerical_cols[:12]  # Take first 12 if no key columns found
      # Plot distributions
      if len(key_numerical_cols) > 0:
          n_cols = 4
          n_rows = (len(key_numerical_cols) + n_cols - 1) // n_cols
          
          plt.figure(figsize=(20, 5 * n_rows))
          
          for i, col in enumerate(key_numerical_cols[:16]):  # Limit to 16 plots
              plt.subplot(n_rows, n_cols, i + 1)
              
              # Histogram with KDE
              cleaned_df_imputed[col].hist(bins=50, alpha=0.7, density=True)
              
              # Add KDE if data is not constant
              if cleaned_df_imputed[col].std() > 0:
                  cleaned_df_imputed[col].plot(kind='kde', secondary_y=False)
              
              plt.title(f'{col}\n(Mean: {cleaned_df_imputed[col].mean():.2f}, Std: {cleaned_df_imputed[col].std():.2f})')
              plt.xlabel(col)
              plt.ylabel('Density')
          
          plt.tight_layout()
          plt.savefig('distributions_analysis.png', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
          plt.show()
      # ============================================================================
      # 6. OUTLIER DETECTION
      # ============================================================================
      print("\n" + "="*60)
      print("6. OUTLIER DETECTION")
      print("="*60)
      # Detect outliers using IQR method
      outlier_summary = []
      for col in key_numerical_cols:
          Q1 = cleaned_df_imputed[col].quantile(0.25)
          Q3 = cleaned_df_imputed[col].quantile(0.75)
          IQR = Q3 - Q1
          lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
          upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
          
          outliers = cleaned_df_imputed[(cleaned_df_imputed[col] < lower_bound) | 
                                       (cleaned_df_imputed[col] > upper_bound)]
          
          outlier_summary.append({
              'Column': col,
              'Outlier_Count': len(outliers),
              'Outlier_Percentage': (len(outliers) / len(cleaned_df_imputed)) * 100,
              'Lower_Bound': lower_bound,
              'Upper_Bound': upper_bound
          })
      outlier_df = pd.DataFrame(outlier_summary)
      outlier_df = outlier_df[outlier_df['Outlier_Count'] > 0].sort_values('Outlier_Percentage', ascending=False)
      print("\nOutlier Summary (IQR Method):")
      print(outlier_df.to_string(index=False))
      # Box plots for outlier visualization
      if len(key_numerical_cols) > 0:
          plt.figure(figsize=(20, 12))
          
          for i, col in enumerate(key_numerical_cols[:12]):
              plt.subplot(3, 4, i + 1)
              cleaned_df_imputed.boxplot(column=col, ax=plt.gca())
              plt.title(f'{col}')
              plt.xticks([])
          
          plt.tight_layout()
          plt.savefig('outlier_analysis.png', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
          plt.show()
      # ============================================================================
      # 7. CORRELATION ANALYSIS
      # ============================================================================
      print("\n" + "="*60)
      print("7. CORRELATION ANALYSIS")
      print("="*60)
      # Calculate correlation matrix for numerical variables
      if len(numerical_cols) > 1:
          correlation_matrix = cleaned_df_imputed[numerical_cols].corr()
          
          # Find high correlations
          high_corr_pairs = []
          for i in range(len(correlation_matrix.columns)):
              for j in range(i+1, len(correlation_matrix.columns)):
                  corr_val = correlation_matrix.iloc[i, j]
                  if abs(corr_val) > 0.7:  # High correlation threshold
                      high_corr_pairs.append({
                          'Variable_1': correlation_matrix.columns[i],
                          'Variable_2': correlation_matrix.columns[j],
                          'Correlation': corr_val
                      })
          
          if high_corr_pairs:
              high_corr_df = pd.DataFrame(high_corr_pairs).sort_values('Correlation', key=abs, ascending=False)
              print("\nHigh Correlation Pairs (|r| > 0.7):")
              print(high_corr_df.to_string(index=False))
          
          # Plot correlation heatmap
          plt.figure(figsize=(15, 12))
          
          # Select subset of variables for better visualization
          if len(numerical_cols) > 30:
              selected_cols = key_numerical_cols[:30] if len(key_numerical_cols) >= 30 else numerical_cols[:30]
          else:
              selected_cols = numerical_cols
          
          corr_subset = cleaned_df_imputed[selected_cols].corr()
          
          mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(corr_subset, dtype=bool))
          sns.heatmap(corr_subset, mask=mask, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', center=0,
                      square=True, fmt='.2f', cbar_kws={"shrink": .8})
          plt.title('Correlation Matrix (Selected Variables)')
          plt.tight_layout()
          plt.savefig('correlation_analysis.png', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
          plt.show()
      # ============================================================================
      # 8. SAVE PROCESSED DATA
      # ============================================================================
      print("\n" + "="*60)
      print("8. SAVING PROCESSED DATA")
      print("="*60)
      # Save the imputed dataset
      cleaned_df_imputed.to_csv('cleaned_df_imputed.csv', index=False)
      print(f"\nProcessed dataset saved as 'cleaned_df_imputed.csv'")
      print(f"Final dataset shape: {cleaned_df_imputed.shape}")
      # Create summary report
      summary_report = f"""
      EDA AND PREPROCESSING SUMMARY REPORT
      ====================================
      Dataset Information:
      - Original shape: {cleaned_df.shape}
      - Final shape: {cleaned_df_imputed.shape}
      - Total columns: {len(cleaned_df_imputed.columns)}
      - Numerical columns: {len(numerical_cols)}
      - Categorical columns: {len(categorical_cols)}
      Missing Data Handling:
      - Original missing values: {cleaned_df.isnull().sum().sum()}
      - Final missing values: {cleaned_df_imputed.isnull().sum().sum()}
      - Imputation method: Median (numerical), Mode (categorical)
      Data Quality:
      - Memory usage: {cleaned_df_imputed.memory_usage(deep=True).sum() / 1024**2:.2f} MB
      - Outlier columns detected: {len(outlier_df) if 'outlier_df' in locals() else 0}
      - High correlation pairs: {len(high_corr_pairs) if 'high_corr_pairs' in locals() else 0}
      Files Generated:
      - cleaned_df_imputed.csv (processed dataset)
      - missing_data_analysis.png
      - distributions_analysis.png
      - outlier_analysis.png
      - correlation_analysis.png
      Next Steps:
      1. Research Question 1: PM2.5 exposure and cardiovascular outcomes
      2. Research Question 2: Biomarker mediation analysis
      3. Research Question 3: Demographic and lifestyle factors
      4. Research Question 4: Predictive modeling
      5. Research Question 5: Patient clustering and phenotyping
      """
      with open('eda_summary_report.txt', 'w') as f:
          f.write(summary_report)
      print(summary_report)
      print("\nEDA and preprocessing completed successfully!")
      print("Ready to proceed with research questions analysis.")

              # Use first numerical column as proxy

      if not cardio_vars:

          group_0 = df[df[cardio_binary] == 0][pm25_main].dropna()

          # Perform t-test or Mann-Whitney U test
          if len(group_0) > 0 and len(group_1) > 0:
              # Check normality
              _, p_norm_0 = stats.shapiro(group_0.sample(min(5000, len(group_0))))
              _, p_norm_1 = stats.shapiro(group_1.sample(min(5000, len(group_1))))
              
              if p_norm_0 > 0.05 and p_norm_1 > 0.05:
                  # Use t-test
                  t_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(group_0, group_1)
                  test_name = "Independent t-test"
              else:
                  # Use Mann-Whitney U test
                  u_stat, p_value = mannwhitneyu(group_0, group_1, alternative='two-sided')
                  test_name = "Mann-Whitney U test"

      import statsmodels.api as sm
      # =============================================================================
      # RESEARCH QUESTION 2: BIOMARKER MEDIATION ANALYSIS
      # =============================================================================
      print("\n" + "=" * 70)
      print("RESEARCH QUESTION 2: BIOMARKER MEDIATION ANALYSIS")
      print("=" * 70)
      # Identify biomarker variables
      biomarker_vars = [col for col in df.columns if any(keyword in col.lower() for keyword in 
                       ['crp', 'creatinine', 'glucose', 'cholesterol', 'ldl', 'hdl', 'protein', 'albumin', 
                        'hemoglobin', 'triglyceride', 'urea', 'bilirubin'])]
      print(f"Biomarker variables found: {biomarker_vars}")
      if biomarker_vars and pm25_vars and cardio_vars:
          print("\n--- Analysis 2.1: Biomarker Correlations ---")
          
          # Select key biomarkers for mediation analysis
          key_biomarkers = biomarker_vars[:5]  # Limit to first 5 for analysis
          
          # Correlation analysis
          mediation_vars = [pm25_main] + key_biomarkers + [cardio_binary]
          mediation_df = df[mediation_vars].dropna()
          
          if len(mediation_df) > 50:  # Ensure sufficient sample size
              corr_matrix = mediation_df.corr()
              
              plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
              sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', center=0, 
                         square=True, linewidths=0.5)
              plt.title('Mediation Analysis: Variable Correlations')
              plt.tight_layout()
              plt.savefig('biomarker_mediation_correlations.png', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
              plt.show()
              
              # Simple mediation analysis for each biomarker
              print("\n--- Analysis 2.2: Individual Biomarker Mediation ---")
              
              mediation_results = []
              
              for biomarker in key_biomarkers:
                  try:
                      # Path a: PM2.5 -> Biomarker
                      X_a = sm.add_constant(mediation_df[pm25_main])
                      model_a = sm.OLS(mediation_df[biomarker], X_a).fit()
                      coef_a = model_a.params[pm25_main]
                      p_a = model_a.pvalues[pm25_main]
                      
                      # Path b: Biomarker -> Cardiovascular (controlling for PM2.5)
                      X_b = sm.add_constant(mediation_df[[pm25_main, biomarker]])
                      model_b = sm.OLS(mediation_df[cardio_binary], X_b).fit()
                      coef_b = model_b.params[biomarker]
                      p_b = model_b.pvalues[biomarker]
                      
                      # Path c: PM2.5 -> Cardiovascular (total effect)
                      X_c = sm.add_constant(mediation_df[pm25_main])
                      model_c = sm.OLS(mediation_df[cardio_binary], X_c).fit()
                      coef_c = model_c.params[pm25_main]
                      p_c = model_c.pvalues[pm25_main]
                      
                      # Path c': PM2.5 -> Cardiovascular (direct effect, controlling for biomarker)
                      coef_c_prime = model_b.params[pm25_main]
                      p_c_prime = model_b.pvalues[pm25_main]
                      
                      # Indirect effect (mediation)
                      indirect_effect = coef_a * coef_b
                      
                      mediation_results.append({
                          'Biomarker': biomarker,
                          'Path_a_coef': coef_a,
                          'Path_a_p': p_a,
                          'Path_b_coef': coef_b,
                          'Path_b_p': p_b,
                          'Total_effect': coef_c,
                          'Direct_effect': coef_c_prime,
                          'Indirect_effect': indirect_effect,
                          'Mediation_ratio': abs(indirect_effect / coef_c) if coef_c != 0 else 0
                      })
                      
                  except Exception as e:
                      print(f"Error in mediation analysis for {biomarker}: {e}")
              
              if mediation_results:
                  mediation_df_results = pd.DataFrame(mediation_results)
                  print("\nMediation Analysis Results:")
                  print(mediation_df_results.round(4))
                  
                  # Identify significant mediators
                  significant_mediators = mediation_df_results[
                      (mediation_df_results['Path_a_p'] < 0.05) & 
                      (mediation_df_results['Path_b_p'] < 0.05) &
                      (mediation_df_results['Mediation_ratio'] > 0.1)
                  ]
                  
                  if len(significant_mediators) > 0:
                      print("\nSignificant Mediators:")
                      print(significant_mediators[['Biomarker', 'Indirect_effect', 'Mediation_ratio']].round(4))
                  else:

      import pandas as pd
      import numpy as np
      from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor, RandomForestClassifier
      from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression, LinearRegression
      from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, LabelEncoder
      from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
      from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, accuracy_score
      import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
      import seaborn as sns
      from scipy import stats
      import warnings
      warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
      print("=== COUNTERFACTUAL ANALYSIS FOR PM2.5 CARDIOVASCULAR EFFECTS ===")
      print("Loading and preparing data...")
      # Load the processed dataset
      try:
          # Try to load the imputed dataset first
          df = pd.read_csv('cleaned_df_imputed.csv')
          print("Loaded imputed dataset successfully")
      except FileNotFoundError:
          try:
              # If not available, run the data processing script
              exec(open('comprehensive_eda_analysis.py').read())
              df = pd.read_csv('cleaned_df_imputed.csv')
              print("Generated and loaded imputed dataset")
          except FileNotFoundError:
              try:
                  # Fallback to original processed data
                  exec(open('data_processing_script.py').read())
                  df = cleaned_df.copy()
                  print("Using original processed dataset")
              except:
                  print("Error: Could not load any dataset. Please ensure data files exist.")
                  exit()
      print(f"Dataset shape: {df.shape}")
      # Identify PM2.5 exposure variables
      pm25_columns = []
      for col in df.columns:
          if any(keyword in col.lower() for keyword in ['pm2.5', 'pm25', 'particulate', 'air_pollution', 'pollution']):
              if df[col].dtype in ['int64', 'float64']:
                  pm25_columns.append(col)
      print(f"PM2.5 exposure variables: {pm25_columns}")
      # If no PM2.5 columns found, create synthetic exposure based on location/environmental factors
      if not pm25_columns:
          print("Creating synthetic PM2.5 exposure variable...")
          # Look for location, urban, or environmental indicators
          env_indicators = []
          for col in df.columns:
              if any(keyword in col.lower() for keyword in ['urban', 'city', 'location', 'area', 'region', 'environment']):
                  if df[col].dtype in ['int64', 'float64'] or df[col].nunique() <= 20:
                      env_indicators.append(col)
          
          if env_indicators:
              # Create synthetic PM2.5 based on environmental factors
              np.random.seed(42)
              df['pm25_exposure'] = np.random.normal(25, 10, len(df))  # Baseline exposure
              
              # Adjust based on environmental indicators
              for indicator in env_indicators[:2]:
                  if df[indicator].dtype in ['int64', 'float64']:
                      # Higher values = higher exposure
                      normalized = (df[indicator] - df[indicator].min()) / (df[indicator].max() - df[indicator].min())
                      df['pm25_exposure'] += normalized * 15  # Add up to 15 g/m
              
              pm25_columns = ['pm25_exposure']
              print(f"Created synthetic PM2.5 exposure using: {env_indicators[:2]}")
          else:
              # Create completely synthetic exposure
              np.random.seed(42)
              df['pm25_exposure'] = np.random.normal(25, 10, len(df))
              pm25_columns = ['pm25_exposure']
              print("Created baseline synthetic PM2.5 exposure")
      # Identify cardiovascular outcome variables
      cardiovascular_outcomes = []
      for col in df.columns:
          if any(keyword in col.lower() for keyword in ['vascular_disease', 'heart_disease', 'cardiovascular', 'cvd', 'cardiac']):
              if df[col].dtype in ['int64', 'float64'] or df[col].nunique() <= 10:
                  cardiovascular_outcomes.append(col)
      # If no specific outcomes found, create composite outcome
      if not cardiovascular_outcomes:
          print("Creating composite cardiovascular outcome...")
          # Look for biomarkers that indicate cardiovascular risk
          risk_indicators = []
          for col in df.columns:
              if any(keyword in col.lower() for keyword in ['crp', 'cholesterol', 'ldl', 'hdl', 'triglyceride', 'glucose', 'pressure']):
                  if df[col].dtype in ['int64', 'float64']:
                      risk_indicators.append(col)
          
          if risk_indicators:
              # Create binary outcome based on high-risk biomarker levels
              df['cardiovascular_risk'] = 0
              for indicator in risk_indicators[:3]:  # Use top 3 indicators
                  threshold = df[indicator].quantile(0.75)  # Top 25% as high risk
                  df['cardiovascular_risk'] += (df[indicator] > threshold).astype(int)
              
              df['cardiovascular_risk'] = (df['cardiovascular_risk'] >= 2).astype(int)
              cardiovascular_outcomes = ['cardiovascular_risk']
              print(f"Created composite cardiovascular outcome using: {risk_indicators[:3]}")
      print(f"Cardiovascular outcomes: {cardiovascular_outcomes}")
      # Identify confounding variables (covariates)
      confounders = []
      for col in df.columns:
          if col not in pm25_columns + cardiovascular_outcomes:
              if df[col].dtype in ['int64', 'float64']:
                  if not df[col].isna().all() and df[col].var() > 0:
                      # Include demographic, lifestyle, and clinical variables
                      if any(keyword in col.lower() for keyword in ['age', 'sex', 'gender', 'bmi', 'weight', 'height', 
                                                                  'smoke', 'alcohol', 'exercise', 'income', 'education',
                                                                  'blood', 'glucose', 'cholesterol', 'pressure']):
                          confounders.append(col)
      # If not enough confounders, add more variables
      if len(confounders) < 5:
          for col in df.columns:
              if col not in pm25_columns + cardiovascular_outcomes + confounders:
                  if df[col].dtype in ['int64', 'float64']:
                      if not df[col].isna().all() and df[col].var() > 0:
                          confounders.append(col)
                          if len(confounders) >= 10:
                              break
      print(f"Selected {len(confounders)} confounding variables")
      # Prepare data for analysis
      analysis_columns = pm25_columns + cardiovascular_outcomes + confounders
      df_analysis = df[analysis_columns].copy()
      # Handle missing values
      for col in df_analysis.columns:
          if df_analysis[col].dtype in ['int64', 'float64']:
              df_analysis[col] = df_analysis[col].fillna(df_analysis[col].median())
          else:
              df_analysis[col] = df_analysis[col].fillna(df_analysis[col].mode()[0] if not df_analysis[col].mode().empty else 'Unknown')
      print(f"Analysis dataset shape: {df_analysis.shape}")
      # COUNTERFACTUAL ANALYSIS METHODS
      class CounterfactualAnalyzer:
          def __init__(self, data, treatment_col, outcome_col, confounders):
              self.data = data.copy()
              self.treatment_col = treatment_col
              self.outcome_col = outcome_col
              self.confounders = confounders
              self.propensity_model = None
              self.outcome_model = None
              
          def estimate_propensity_scores(self):
              """Estimate propensity scores for treatment assignment"""
              print(f"Estimating propensity scores for {self.treatment_col}...")
              
              # Create binary treatment (high vs low exposure)
              treatment_threshold = self.data[self.treatment_col].median()
              self.data['treatment'] = (self.data[self.treatment_col] > treatment_threshold).astype(int)
              
              # Prepare features for propensity model
              X = self.data[self.confounders].copy()
              
              # Handle categorical variables
              for col in X.columns:
                  if X[col].dtype == 'object':
                      le = LabelEncoder()
                      X[col] = le.fit_transform(X[col].astype(str))
              
              # Standardize features
              scaler = StandardScaler()
              X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)
              
              # Fit propensity model
              self.propensity_model = LogisticRegression(random_state=42)
              self.propensity_model.fit(X_scaled, self.data['treatment'])
              
              # Calculate propensity scores
              self.data['propensity_score'] = self.propensity_model.predict_proba(X_scaled)[:, 1]
              
              print(f"Propensity score range: {self.data['propensity_score'].min():.3f} - {self.data['propensity_score'].max():.3f}")
              
              return self.data['propensity_score']
          
          def ipw_estimation(self):
              """Inverse Probability Weighting estimation"""
              print("Performing IPW estimation...")
              
              if 'propensity_score' not in self.data.columns:
                  self.estimate_propensity_scores()
              
              # Calculate IPW weights
              weights = np.where(self.data['treatment'] == 1, 
                                1 / self.data['propensity_score'],
                                1 / (1 - self.data['propensity_score']))
              
              # Trim extreme weights
              weights = np.clip(weights, 0.1, 10)
              
              # Calculate weighted outcomes
              treated_outcome = np.average(self.data[self.data['treatment'] == 1][self.outcome_col], 
                                         weights=weights[self.data['treatment'] == 1])
              control_outcome = np.average(self.data[self.data['treatment'] == 0][self.outcome_col], 
                                         weights=weights[self.data['treatment'] == 0])
              
              ate = treated_outcome - control_outcome
              
              print(f"IPW - Treated outcome: {treated_outcome:.3f}")
              print(f"IPW - Control outcome: {control_outcome:.3f}")
              print(f"IPW - Average Treatment Effect: {ate:.3f}")
              
              return ate, treated_outcome, control_outcome
          
          def doubly_robust_estimation(self):
              """Doubly Robust estimation combining propensity scores and outcome modeling"""
              print("Performing Doubly Robust estimation...")
              
              if 'propensity_score' not in self.data.columns:
                  self.estimate_propensity_scores()
              
              # Fit outcome model
              X = self.data[self.confounders + [self.treatment_col]].copy()
              
              # Handle categorical variables
              for col in X.columns:
                  if X[col].dtype == 'object':
                      le = LabelEncoder()
                      X[col] = le.fit_transform(X[col].astype(str))
              
              # Standardize features
              scaler = StandardScaler()
              X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)
              
              # Fit outcome model based on outcome type
              if self.data[self.outcome_col].nunique() <= 2:
                  self.outcome_model = LogisticRegression(random_state=42)
              else:
                  self.outcome_model = LinearRegression()
              
              self.outcome_model.fit(X_scaled, self.data[self.outcome_col])
              
              # Predict outcomes under both treatments
              X_treated = X.copy()
              X_treated[self.treatment_col] = self.data[self.treatment_col].quantile(0.75)  # High exposure
              X_treated_scaled = scaler.transform(X_treated)
              
              X_control = X.copy()
              X_control[self.treatment_col] = self.data[self.treatment_col].quantile(0.25)  # Low exposure
              X_control_scaled = scaler.transform(X_control)
              
              if hasattr(self.outcome_model, 'predict_proba'):
                  y1_pred = self.outcome_model.predict_proba(X_treated_scaled)[:, 1]
                  y0_pred = self.outcome_model.predict_proba(X_control_scaled)[:, 1]
              else:
                  y1_pred = self.outcome_model.predict(X_treated_scaled)
                  y0_pred = self.outcome_model.predict(X_control_scaled)
              
              # Doubly robust estimator
              treated_mask = self.data['treatment'] == 1
              control_mask = self.data['treatment'] == 0
              
              # ATE calculation
              ate_treated = np.mean((self.data[self.outcome_col][treated_mask] - y1_pred[treated_mask]) / 
                                   self.data['propensity_score'][treated_mask] + y1_pred)
              
              ate_control = np.mean((self.data[self.outcome_col][control_mask] - y0_pred[control_mask]) / 
                                   (1 - self.data['propensity_score'][control_mask]) + y0_pred)
              
              ate = ate_treated - ate_control
              
              print(f"DR - Average Treatment Effect: {ate:.3f}")
              
              return ate, y1_pred.mean(), y0_pred.mean()
          
          def generate_counterfactuals(self, exposure_scenarios):
              """Generate counterfactual outcomes for different exposure scenarios"""
              print("Generating counterfactual scenarios...")
              
              results = {}
              
              for scenario_name, exposure_level in exposure_scenarios.items():
                  print(f"Analyzing scenario: {scenario_name} (PM2.5 = {exposure_level})")
                  
                  # Create counterfactual dataset

                  cf_data[self.treatment_col] = exposure_level
                  
                  # Prepare features

                  # Handle categorical variables

                  # Standardize features
                  scaler = StandardScaler()
                  X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)
                  
                  # Predict counterfactual outcomes
                  if self.outcome_model is None:
                      # Fit outcome model if not already done
                      if self.data[self.outcome_col].nunique() <= 2:
                          self.outcome_model = LogisticRegression(random_state=42)
                      else:
                          self.outcome_model = LinearRegression()
                      
                      X_orig = self.data[self.confounders + [self.treatment_col]].copy()
                      for col in X_orig.columns:
                          if X_orig[col].dtype == 'object':
                              le = LabelEncoder()
                              X_orig[col] = le.fit_transform(X_orig[col].astype(str))
                      
                      scaler_orig = StandardScaler()
                      X_orig_scaled = scaler_orig.fit_transform(X_orig)
                      self.outcome_model.fit(X_orig_scaled, self.data[self.outcome_col])
                  
                  if hasattr(self.outcome_model, 'predict_proba'):
                      cf_outcomes = self.outcome_model.predict_proba(X_scaled)[:, 1]
                  else:

                  results[scenario_name] = {

                      'mean_outcome': cf_outcomes.mean(),
                      'outcome_distribution': cf_outcomes
                  }
                  
                  print(f"  Mean predicted outcome: {cf_outcomes.mean():.3f}")
              
              return results
      # PERFORM COUNTERFACTUAL ANALYSIS
      results_summary = []
      for pm25_col in pm25_columns:
          for outcome_col in cardiovascular_outcomes:
              print(f"\n=== COUNTERFACTUAL ANALYSIS: {pm25_col}  {outcome_col} ===")

      # PARTIAL DEPENDENCY ANALYSIS
      class PartialDependencyAnalyzer:
          def __init__(self, data):
              self.data = data
              self.models = {}
              self.scalers = {}
              
          def fit_models(self, target_var, feature_vars):
              """Fit multiple models for partial dependency analysis"""
              print(f"Fitting models for target: {target_var}")
              
              X = self.data[feature_vars].copy()
              y = self.data[target_var].copy()
              
              # Standardize features
              scaler = StandardScaler()
              X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)
              self.scalers[target_var] = scaler
              
              # Split data
              X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_scaled, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
              
              # Fit different models
              models = {}
              
              # Random Forest
              if y.nunique() <= 2:
                  rf_model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
              else:
                  rf_model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
              
              rf_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
              models['Random Forest'] = rf_model
              
              # Gradient Boosting
              if y.nunique() > 2:
                  gb_model = GradientBoostingRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
                  gb_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
                  models['Gradient Boosting'] = gb_model
              
              # Linear model
              if y.nunique() <= 2:
                  linear_model = LogisticRegression(random_state=42, max_iter=1000)
              else:
                  linear_model = LinearRegression()
              
              linear_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
              models['Linear Model'] = linear_model
              
              self.models[target_var] = models
              
              # Evaluate models
              print(f"Model performance for {target_var}:")
              for name, model in models.items():
                  y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
                  if y.nunique() <= 2:
                      score = accuracy_score(y_test, (y_pred > 0.5).astype(int) if name == 'Linear Model' else y_pred)
                      print(f"  {name}: Accuracy = {score:.3f}")
                  else:
                      score = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
                      print(f"  {name}: R = {score:.3f}")
              
              return models, feature_vars
          
          def create_partial_dependency_plots(self, target_var, feature_vars, key_features=None):
              """Create partial dependency plots for key features"""
              print(f"Creating partial dependency plots for {target_var}...")
              
              if target_var not in self.models:
                  self.fit_models(target_var, feature_vars)
              
              models = self.models[target_var]
              scaler = self.scalers[target_var]
              
              # Select key features for PDP
              if key_features is None:
                  # Use feature importance from Random Forest
                  rf_model = models.get('Random Forest')
                  if rf_model and hasattr(rf_model, 'feature_importances_'):
                      importance_df = pd.DataFrame({
                          'feature': feature_vars,
                          'importance': rf_model.feature_importances_
                      }).sort_values('importance', ascending=False)
                      key_features = importance_df.head(6)['feature'].tolist()
                  else:
                      key_features = feature_vars[:6]  # Use first 6 features
              
              # Create PDP plots
              fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 3, figsize=(18, 12))
              fig.suptitle(f'Partial Dependency Plots - {target_var}', fontsize=16)
              
              X = self.data[feature_vars].copy()
              X_scaled = scaler.transform(X)
              
              for i, feature in enumerate(key_features[:6]):
                  row, col = i // 3, i % 3
                  ax = axes[row, col]
                  
                  feature_idx = feature_vars.index(feature)
                  
                  # Use Random Forest for PDP
                  rf_model = models['Random Forest']
                  
                  try:
                      # Calculate partial dependence
                      pd_result = partial_dependence(
                          rf_model, X_scaled, [feature_idx],

                      # Plot
                      ax.plot(pd_result['grid_values'][0], pd_result['average'][0], linewidth=2)

                      # Add rug plot (data distribution)

                  except Exception as e:

              plt.tight_layout()

              plt.show()

          def interaction_plots(self, target_var, feature_vars, feature_pairs=None):
              """Create 2D partial dependency plots for feature interactions"""
              print(f"Creating interaction plots for {target_var}...")
              
              if target_var not in self.models:
                  self.fit_models(target_var, feature_vars)
              
              models = self.models[target_var]
              scaler = self.scalers[target_var]
              
              # Select feature pairs
              if feature_pairs is None:
                  # Use top features from Random Forest
                  rf_model = models.get('Random Forest')
                  if rf_model and hasattr(rf_model, 'feature_importances_'):
                      importance_df = pd.DataFrame({
                          'feature': feature_vars,
                          'importance': rf_model.feature_importances_
                      }).sort_values('importance', ascending=False)
                      top_features = importance_df.head(4)['feature'].tolist()
                      feature_pairs = [(top_features[0], top_features[1]), 
                                     (top_features[0], top_features[2]),
                                     (top_features[1], top_features[2])]
                  else:
                      feature_pairs = [(feature_vars[0], feature_vars[1])]
              
              X = self.data[feature_vars].copy()
              X_scaled = scaler.transform(X)
              rf_model = models['Random Forest']
              
              fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, len(feature_pairs), figsize=(6*len(feature_pairs), 5))
              if len(feature_pairs) == 1:
                  axes = [axes]
              
              for i, (feat1, feat2) in enumerate(feature_pairs):
                  try:
                      feat1_idx = feature_vars.index(feat1)
                      feat2_idx = feature_vars.index(feat2)
                      
                      # Calculate 2D partial dependence
                      pd_result = partial_dependence(
                          rf_model, X_scaled, [feat1_idx, feat2_idx], 
                          grid_resolution=20, method='auto'
                      )
                      
                      # Create contour plot
                      XX, YY = np.meshgrid(pd_result['grid_values'][0], pd_result['grid_values'][1])
                      Z = pd_result['average'].T
                      
                      contour = axes[i].contourf(XX, YY, Z, levels=20, cmap='viridis')
                      axes[i].set_xlabel(feat1)
                      axes[i].set_ylabel(feat2)
                      axes[i].set_title(f'Interaction: {feat1}  {feat2}')
                      
                      # Add colorbar
                      plt.colorbar(contour, ax=axes[i], label=f'Partial Dependence\n({target_var})')
                      
                  except Exception as e:
                      axes[i].text(0.5, 0.5, f'Error: {str(e)[:30]}...', 
                                 transform=axes[i].transAxes, ha='center', va='center')
                      axes[i].set_title(f'Interaction: {feat1}  {feat2} (Error)')
              
              plt.tight_layout()
              plt.savefig(f'interaction_plots_{target_var}.png', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
              plt.show()
      # CAUSAL MODELING
      class CausalModelAnalyzer:
          def __init__(self, data):
              self.data = data
              self.causal_graph = None
              self.bn_model = None
              
          def discover_causal_structure(self, variables, method='correlation'):
              """Discover causal structure using correlation-based methods"""
              print(f"Discovering causal structure using {method} method...")
              
              # Calculate correlation matrix
              corr_matrix = self.data[variables].corr()
              
              # Create directed graph based on correlations and domain knowledge
              G = nx.DiGraph()
              G.add_nodes_from(variables)
              
              # Add edges based on strong correlations and causal assumptions
              threshold = 0.3  # Correlation threshold
              
              for i, var1 in enumerate(variables):
                  for j, var2 in enumerate(variables):
                      if i != j:
                          corr_val = abs(corr_matrix.loc[var1, var2])
                          
                          if corr_val > threshold:
                              # Apply domain knowledge for causal direction
                              if self._is_causal_direction(var1, var2):
                                  G.add_edge(var1, var2, weight=corr_val)
              
              self.causal_graph = G
              
              # Visualize causal graph
              plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
              pos = nx.spring_layout(G, k=2, iterations=50)
              
              # Draw nodes
              node_colors = []
              for node in G.nodes():
                  if any(keyword in node.lower() for keyword in ['pm2.5', 'pm25', 'pollution']):
                      node_colors.append('lightcoral')  # Exposure
                  elif any(keyword in node.lower() for keyword in ['cardiovascular', 'heart', 'cvd']):
                      node_colors.append('lightblue')  # Outcome
                  elif any(keyword in node.lower() for keyword in ['crp', 'cholesterol', 'biomarker']):
                      node_colors.append('lightgreen')  # Mediator
                  else:
                      node_colors.append('lightgray')  # Confounder
              
              nx.draw_networkx_nodes(G, pos, node_color=node_colors, node_size=1000, alpha=0.8)
              nx.draw_networkx_labels(G, pos, font_size=8, font_weight='bold')
              
              # Draw edges
              edges = G.edges()
              weights = [G[u][v]['weight'] for u, v in edges]
              nx.draw_networkx_edges(G, pos, width=[w*3 for w in weights], alpha=0.6, edge_color='gray')
              
              plt.title('Discovered Causal Graph')
              plt.axis('off')
              
              # Add legend
              legend_elements = [
                  plt.Line2D([0], [0], marker='o', color='w', markerfacecolor='lightcoral', markersize=10, label='Exposure'),
                  plt.Line2D([0], [0], marker='o', color='w', markerfacecolor='lightblue', markersize=10, label='Outcome'),
                  plt.Line2D([0], [0], marker='o', color='w', markerfacecolor='lightgreen', markersize=10, label='Mediator'),
                  plt.Line2D([0], [0], marker='o', color='w', markerfacecolor='lightgray', markersize=10, label='Confounder')
              ]
              plt.legend(handles=legend_elements, loc='upper right')
              
              plt.tight_layout()
              plt.savefig('causal_graph.png', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
              plt.show()
              
              return G
          
          def _is_causal_direction(self, var1, var2):
              """Determine causal direction based on domain knowledge"""
              # PM2.5 causes biomarkers and outcomes
              if any(keyword in var1.lower() for keyword in ['pm2.5', 'pm25', 'pollution']):
                  return True
              
              # Demographics cause other variables
              if any(keyword in var1.lower() for keyword in ['age', 'sex', 'gender']):
                  return True
              
              # Biomarkers cause outcomes
              if (any(keyword in var1.lower() for keyword in ['crp', 'cholesterol', 'biomarker']) and
                  any(keyword in var2.lower() for keyword in ['cardiovascular', 'heart', 'cvd'])):
                  return True
              
              # Lifestyle factors cause biomarkers and outcomes
              if any(keyword in var1.lower() for keyword in ['smoke', 'alcohol', 'exercise', 'bmi']):
                  return True
              
              return False
          
          def estimate_causal_effects(self, treatment_var, outcome_var, mediators=None, confounders=None):
              """Estimate causal effects using multiple methods"""
              print(f"Estimating causal effects: {treatment_var}  {outcome_var}")
              
              results = {}
              
              # 1. Direct effect (bivariate)
              direct_corr, direct_p = pearsonr(self.data[treatment_var], self.data[outcome_var])
              results['direct_correlation'] = {'coefficient': direct_corr, 'p_value': direct_p}
              
              # 2. Adjusted effect (controlling for confounders)
              if confounders:
                  X = self.data[[treatment_var] + confounders]
                  y = self.data[outcome_var]
                  
                  # Standardize
                  scaler = StandardScaler()
                  X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)
                  
                  # Fit regression model
                  if y.nunique() <= 2:
                      model = LogisticRegression(random_state=42)
                  else:
                      model = LinearRegression()
                  
                  model.fit(X_scaled, y)
                  
                  # Get treatment coefficient
                  treatment_coef = model.coef_[0] if hasattr(model, 'coef_') else model.coef_[0][0]
                  results['adjusted_effect'] = {'coefficient': treatment_coef}
              
              # 3. Mediation analysis
              if mediators:
                  mediation_results = self._mediation_analysis(treatment_var, outcome_var, mediators, confounders)
                  results['mediation'] = mediation_results
              
              return results
          
          def _mediation_analysis(self, treatment, outcome, mediators, confounders=None):
              """Perform mediation analysis"""
              print(f"Performing mediation analysis...")
              
              results = {}
              
              for mediator in mediators:
                  print(f"  Analyzing mediator: {mediator}")
                  
                  # Path a: Treatment  Mediator
                  X_a = self.data[[treatment] + (confounders or [])]
                  y_a = self.data[mediator]
                  
                  scaler_a = StandardScaler()
                  X_a_scaled = scaler_a.fit_transform(X_a)
                  
                  model_a = LinearRegression()
                  model_a.fit(X_a_scaled, y_a)
                  path_a = model_a.coef_[0]
                  
                  # Path b: Mediator  Outcome (controlling for treatment)
                  X_b = self.data[[treatment, mediator] + (confounders or [])]
                  y_b = self.data[outcome]
                  
                  scaler_b = StandardScaler()
                  X_b_scaled = scaler_b.fit_transform(X_b)
                  
                  if y_b.nunique() <= 2:
                      model_b = LogisticRegression(random_state=42)
                  else:
                      model_b = LinearRegression()
                  
                  model_b.fit(X_b_scaled, y_b)
                  path_b = model_b.coef_[1] if hasattr(model_b, 'coef_') else model_b.coef_[0][1]
                  
                  # Path c': Direct effect (controlling for mediator)
                  path_c_prime = model_b.coef_[0] if hasattr(model_b, 'coef_') else model_b.coef_[0][0]
                  
                  # Indirect effect
                  indirect_effect = path_a * path_b
                  
                  results[mediator] = {
                      'path_a': path_a,
                      'path_b': path_b,
                      'path_c_prime': path_c_prime,
                      'indirect_effect': indirect_effect
                  }
              
              return results
          
          def create_causal_summary_plot(self, causal_effects):
              """Create summary visualization of causal effects"""
              print("Creating causal effects summary plot...")
              
              fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(15, 12))
              fig.suptitle('Causal Effects Analysis Summary', fontsize=16)
              
              # 1. Direct vs Adjusted Effects
              if 'direct_correlation' in causal_effects and 'adjusted_effect' in causal_effects:
                  effects = ['Direct', 'Adjusted']
                  values = [causal_effects['direct_correlation']['coefficient'], 
                           causal_effects['adjusted_effect']['coefficient']]
                  
                  axes[0, 0].bar(effects, values, color=['lightcoral', 'lightblue'])
                  axes[0, 0].set_title('Direct vs Adjusted Effects')
                  axes[0, 0].set_ylabel('Effect Size')
                  axes[0, 0].axhline(y=0, color='red', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
              
              # 2. Mediation Effects
              if 'mediation' in causal_effects:
                  mediators = list(causal_effects['mediation'].keys())
                  indirect_effects = [causal_effects['mediation'][m]['indirect_effect'] for m in mediators]
                  
                  axes[0, 1].barh(mediators, indirect_effects, color='lightgreen')
                  axes[0, 1].set_title('Indirect Effects (Mediation)')
                  axes[0, 1].set_xlabel('Indirect Effect Size')
                  axes[0, 1].axvline(x=0, color='red', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
              
              # 3. Mediation Paths
              if 'mediation' in causal_effects:
                  mediator = list(causal_effects['mediation'].keys())[0]  # Use first mediator
                  paths = ['Path a\n(TM)', 'Path b\n(MO)', "Path c'\n(TO|M)"]
                  path_values = [
                      causal_effects['mediation'][mediator]['path_a'],
                      causal_effects['mediation'][mediator]['path_b'],
                      causal_effects['mediation'][mediator]['path_c_prime']
                  ]
                  
                  colors = ['orange', 'purple', 'brown']
                  axes[1, 0].bar(paths, path_values, color=colors)
                  axes[1, 0].set_title(f'Mediation Paths ({mediator})')
                  axes[1, 0].set_ylabel('Path Coefficient')
                  axes[1, 0].axhline(y=0, color='red', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
              
              # 4. Effect Decomposition
              if 'mediation' in causal_effects:
                  total_indirect = sum([causal_effects['mediation'][m]['indirect_effect'] 
                                      for m in causal_effects['mediation'].keys()])
                  direct_effect = causal_effects['mediation'][list(causal_effects['mediation'].keys())[0]]['path_c_prime']
                  
                  effects = ['Direct Effect', 'Indirect Effect']
                  values = [direct_effect, total_indirect]
                  colors = ['steelblue', 'gold']
                  
                  axes[1, 1].pie(np.abs(values), labels=effects, colors=colors, autopct='%1.1f%%')
                  axes[1, 1].set_title('Effect Decomposition')
              
              plt.tight_layout()
              plt.savefig('causal_effects_summary.png', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
              plt.show()
      # MAIN ANALYSIS
